Internally, it has driven improvements in how we source materials, manage production and optimise logistics. It has created a framework for continuous improvement, ensuring sustainability is embedded into everyday decision making rather than handled as a one off initiative.

Externally, it has strengthened trust with customers. Many organisations are now required to report on their environmental impact, and working with a certified carbon neutral supplier helps them meet those goals. It also provides clear, credible evidence that our claims are backed by recognised standards.

Overall, it has positioned us as a serious, accountable partner in the sustainability space and has opened doors to new opportunities, particularly within larger organisations and public sector frameworks.

### You started with a .uk domain for your business. Why did you switch to .eco?

Switching to a .eco domain was a deliberate decision to better align our brand with our purpose. As a business built around sustainability, we wanted our digital presence to clearly reflect our environmental focus from the first interaction.

The .eco domain signals that commitment instantly. It places us within a global community of organisations working towards positive environmental change, rather than being seen as a standard commercial supplier.

It also supports transparency and credibility. Customers are increasingly conscious of greenwashing, so having a domain that is directly linked to environmental values helps reinforce that sustainability is at the core of what we do, not an afterthought.

From a commercial perspective, it has also helped differentiate us in a competitive market. The domain is memorable, relevant and clearly communicates our positioning. Combined with our operational practices, it strengthens our overall brand message and helps attract customers who prioritise sustainability in their supply chain decisions.

